2) Normalization to 167 reads per sample

Let’s normalize the original dataset by randomly subsampling 167 reads in each station:

library(vegan)
tp_vp_16SmiTags_c_v2_t<-t(tp_vp_16SmiTags_c_v2)
tp_16mt_c_ss167<-rrarefy(tp_vp_16SmiTags_c_v2_t, 167)

3) General community analysis

3.1) Richness and evenness (Shannon index)

Most of the samples take Shannon Index values between 3.25 and 3.75:

3.2) Richness: OTU number

Lowest number of OTUs per sample:

## [1] 23

Maximum number of OTUs per sample:

## [1] 113

In most of the samples, we can identify between 50 and 70 OTUs:

plot(sort(OTUs_per_sample_tp_16mt_c_ss167), pch=19)

boxplot(OTUs_per_sample_tp_16mt_c_ss167, pch=19)

3.3) Index of evenness

3.3.1) Pielou’s index

pielou_c_venness_tp_16mt_c_ss167 <- tp_16mt_c_ss167_div/log(OTUs_per_sample_tp_16mt_c_ss167)

The Pielou index (constrained between 0 and 1) takes values closer to 1 as the variation of species proportion in a sample decreases. Most of our samples get values between 0.8 and 0.9, meaning that the numerical composition of different OTUs within our samples is so similar:

plot(sort(pielou_c_venness_tp_16mt_c_ss167), pch=19)

boxplot(pielou_c_venness_tp_16mt_c_ss167, pch=19)

The OTU_1417, with 2383 reads, is the most abundant in the overall dataset:

head(sort(colSums(tp_16mt_c_ss167_no_cero), decreasing=T), n=10L)

3.4) Abundance Models

3.4.2) Preston’s Lognormal Model

According to Preston’s lognormal model fit into species frequencies groups, we’re missing ~1557 species:

tp_16mt_c_ss167_prestonfit<-prestonfit(colSums(tp_vp_16SmiTags_c_v2_t))
plot(tp_16mt_c_ss167_prestonfit, main="Pooled species")

veiledspec(tp_16mt_c_ss167_prestonfit)
## Extrapolated     Observed       Veiled 
##     3540.205     1983.000     1557.205

When computing Preston’s lognormal model fit without pooling data into groups, we seem to miss ~1166 species:

## Extrapolated     Observed       Veiled 
##       3148.7       1983.0       1165.7

3.6) Beta diversity

3.6.1) Dissimilarity matrix using Bray-Curtis index:

The Bray-Curtis dissimilarity, constrained between 0 (minimum distance) and 1 (highest dissimilarity) allows us to quantify the differences between samples according to the composition and relative abundance of their OTUs. In our dataset, most of the samples pairs take dissimilarity values between 0.7 and 0.9, meaning that their composition is substantially different.

3.6.2) Hierarchical clustering

We do observe distinguished clusters; we’ll need to implement further analysis to determine if the observed groups are meaningful.

(To be done: add Longhurst provinces and sampling depth information)

3.6.3) Non-metric multidimensional scaling

In general terms, we can distinguish a big cluster in the middle of the chart and even a weak group clustering in the middle-right side of the edge.

The stress parameter takes a value below 0.3, meaning that the plot is valid.
